s though they belong in modern societies, and which bodies are treated as unwanted. It considers how people challenge and manage these unfair standards, illuminating what it means to be large-bodied in America’s diet-obsessed culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aEthnologyxMethodology. 0aGastric bypass. 0aObesityxSocial aspects. 0aObesityxSurgeryvPopular works. 0aObesity. 0aWeight loss. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh  aanthropology.  abariatric surgery.  abody mass indices (BMI).  achronicity.  adiet.  adieting.  adiscrimination.  adumping.  aethnography.  afailure.  afat stigma.  afat.  agastric bypass.  ahope.  aloose skin.  amisfitting.  anoncompliance.  anormal.  aobesity.  aoverweight.  aqualitative data collection.  arestrictive eating.  asocial norms.  astigma.  asurveillance.  atype 2 diabetes.  aweight loss.  aweight.  aworry.1 aBrewis, Alexandra, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aWutich, Amber, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut40uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9781479879274.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479879274423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781479879274/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles